      • convertSymbolsForSaving

        public static String convertSymbolsForSaving(String str)
        Converts a set of symbols that are used within the serializing functions to prevent data corruption, as well as any ChatColor characters(it changes them to their respective '&' codes).
        Parameters:
        str - String
        Returns:
        The given string, with certain symbols changed to keep inventory formatting from getting broken because of a simple character.
        See Also:
        convertSymbolsForLoading(String str)

      • serializeInventory

        public static String serializeInventory(org.bukkit.inventory.ItemStack[] items,
                        int invSize,
                        String invTitle)
        Serializes the given inventory and converts and saves all data that may be associated with the items within the inventory.

        Serialization tags(for easy readability):
        0# = The slot number(where 0 is the first slot in the hotbar of a player's inventory)
        t@ = Item Type(Notice this one is NOT prefixed with a colon)
        :d@ = Item Durability
        :a@ = Item Amount
        :e@ = Item Enchantment Data
        :l@ = Item Lore Data
        :n@ = Item Name
        :b@ = Book Data
        :z@ = Enchanted Book Data
        :k@ = Skull Item
        :f@ = Firework Item Data
        You can add an additional '@' after a tag to specify additional data if it has the word 'Data' in it's name above.

        An example of a player inventory, containing a Stone Pickaxe, with the custom Name "Hello, world!" and some enchantments and lore:
        36;container.inventory;0#t@274:d@60:e@34@3: e@35@1:e@32@2:n@&3Hello, world!:l@&4The item's Lore, Line One@&2The Item's Lore, Line Two@Etc, &3etc.;
        The "36;" is the size of the inventory(in slots), and the "container.inventory;" is the title of the inventory(That is the default Minecraft title, anything else that you type here will be displayed instead of 'Inventory').
        Deleting these two stored values will render the whole inventory un-readable, and upon being read from by deserializeInventory(String), will be returned null.

        Parameters:
        inv - Inventory
        Returns:
        The given Inventory, serialized into a single-line String.

        See Also:
        InventoryAPI#serializeInventory(Player, String)}
        {@link InventoryAPI#serializeInventory(Player)}
        {@link InventoryAPI#deserializeInventory(String)}
        {@link InventoryAPI#deserializeInventory(String, Player)}
        {@link InventoryAPI#serializeBook(ItemStack)}
        {@link InventoryAPI#deserializeBook(ItemStack, String[])}

      • serializeInventory

        public static String serializeInventory(org.bukkit.entity.Player player,
                        String invToConvert)
        With this function allows you to easily choose what Inventory is to be used from the given Player in the function serializeInventory(Inventory), and have it returned all in the same function.
        With the parameter invToConvert, you can specify either "inventory", "armor", or "enderchest", and the function will return the serialized inventory of the type that you specified.
        Parameters:
        player - Player
        invToConvert - String
        Returns:
        The serialized inventory as a single-line String. If the Player parameter is null, then a blank String is returned. If the String parameter is null, or isn't one of the options listed, the player's default inventory is returned, serialized as a single-line String. If both the Player and the String parameters are null, a blank String is returned.
        See Also:
        InventoryAPI#serializeInventory(Inventory)}
        {@link InventoryAPI#serializeInventory(Player)}
        {@link InventoryAPI#deserializeInventory(String)}
        {@link InventoryAPI#deserializeInventory(String, Player)}
        {@link InventoryAPI#serializeBook(ItemStack)}
        {@link InventoryAPI#deserializeBook(ItemStack, String[])}

      • deserializeBook

        public static org.bukkit.inventory.ItemStack deserializeBook(org.bukkit.inventory.ItemStack item,
                                             String[] itemAttribute)
        Attempts to deserialize the BookMeta data from the String[] parameter and add it to the given ItemStack, which is then returned. If no ItemStack is given, a Written Book is generated in its place, and the BookMeta assigned. If no String[] parameter is given, then this function will return the given ItemStack, or a blank Book and Quill if no ItemStack was given either.
        Parameters:
        item - ItemStack
        itemAttribute - String[]
        Returns:
        The deserialized Book, with all of its previous BookMeta intact. If the String[] parameter is null, then this will return the given ItemStack.
        See Also:
        InventoryAPI#serializeBook(ItemStack)}
        {@link InventoryAPI#serializeInventory(Inventory)}
        {@link InventoryAPI#serializeInventory(Player, String)}
        {@link InventoryAPI#serializeInventory(Player)}
        {@link InventoryAPI#deserializeInventory(String)}
        {@link InventoryAPI#deserializeInventory(String, Player)}

      • deserializeExperience

        public static String[] deserializeExperience(String serializedExp)
        Attempts to return a String[] array containing the Integer level and the float experience, deserialized from the String parameter.
        Parameters:
        serializedExp - String
        Returns:
        A String[] array containing the Integer level and the float experience, deserialized from the String parameter. May return values that are not an Integer or a float in the String[] array, so it is recommended to either check the result of this function or use one(or both) of the following functions instead:
        deserializeExp(String)
        deserializeLevel(String)
        See Also:
